research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/results.tsv:46:proxy_1774099713	1774099713	proxy	crash	crash									1ece1ddf907bf98341413e31b933a58538d45fef	autoresearch-sae	True	Register and enable the `factorized_topk` architecture in `sparsify/`, then rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the current signum baseline.	This is the smallest defensible next step because the latest failure is an explicit compatibility bug, not a quality result, and continuing to retry without fixing registration would waste rounds. The main risk is that the family still underperforms once it runs, but one valid proxy result is required before deciding whether to stabilize or retire it.	/root/sparsify-ascend/research/history/logs/proxy_1774099713.log
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/results.tsv:56:proxy_1774102171	1774102171	proxy	crash	crash									697318fe5073896f69945d6bc458358907c1f5b1	autoresearch-sae	True	Register and implement the `residual_topk` architecture in `sparsify/`, then rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the current best signum settings.	This is the minimal blocker-removal step after a concrete architecture-registration crash, and it keeps the round focused on making the intended new family runnable rather than changing the experimental target. The main risk is that a second incompatibility appears after registration, but that is still better handled as a code-fix path than by abandoning the family without a valid signal.	/root/sparsify-ascend/research/history/logs/proxy_1774102171.log
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/results.tsv:61:proxy_1774103471	1774103471	proxy	crash	crash									7cdb13220ee52f91eec8027de3fc1765290d5dc1	autoresearch-sae	True	Add `residual_topk` support under `sparsify/` and rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the existing signum regime.	This follows the operator guidance to fix architecture-specific blockers before drawing quality conclusions, and it keeps the round focused on a single variable: making the blocked family runnable. The main risk is that registration is not the only incompatibility, but even that outcome is more informative than spending another round on incremental gated tuning.	/root/sparsify-ascend/research/history/logs/proxy_1774103471.log
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/results.tsv:141:proxy_1774163999	1774163999	proxy	crash	crash		40	codebook_topk	8				/root/sparsify-ascend/checkpoints/research_agent/round_0058_proxy/round0058_proxy_1774163969_dp2_bs1_ga8_ef8_k40_20260322_151935	18a486855f2c5f678892bd0cc7cfe39251fe2955	autoresearch-sae	True	Make a narrow `code_fix` in `sparsify/` for `codebook_topk` to eliminate the DDP unused-parameter failure observed at `K=40`, `EF=8`, then rerun the same proxy recipe unchanged to get a valid signal for this architecture family.	This keeps the round focused on a concrete blocker rather than resuming unproductive hyperparameter search, respects the same-EF comparison target, and follows the runtime guidance to fix architecture-local compatibility issues before drawing architecture conclusions from a crash. The main risk is that the family remains weak even after the fix, but a clean run is more informative than another architecture hop under a known failure mode.	/root/sparsify-ascend/research/history/logs/proxy_1774163999.log
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/session_brief.json:774:      "message": "When a new architecture crashes with a clear implementation or DDP compatibility error, treat that as an implementation blocker rather than an\n  architecture verdict. If the direction is still strategically valuable, do one narrow repair-focused follow-up before abandoning it; do not mix crash outcomes\n  with quality conclusions.",
