research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/memory.json:8:    "round 41: `product_codebook_topk` did not fail on quality; it failed because the runtime still does not recognize the new architecture name. The next highest-value move is a narrow compatibility repair in the architecture validation/factory path so the discrete additive-codebook family can produce a real proxy signal before we decide whether to keep or archive this branch. -> crash (fvu=None, observed_fvu=, k=None, health=crash, termination=completed)",
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/memory.json:9:    "round 58: The `K=40`, `EF=8` regime now appears broadly exhausted on quality and `codebook_topk` additionally exposed a concrete distributed-training compatibility failure, so the least-bad next move is a narrow code-fix round rather than another blind architecture swap. Repairing `codebook_topk` so all trainable paths participate in loss is the smallest informative step to determine whether the discrete-retrieval direction is actually bad or was obscured by a DDP-unused-parameter bug. -> crash (fvu=None, observed_fvu=None, k=None, health=crash, termination=identical_to_baseline)",
